@flexiarg vsatlatarium/embodied-browsing
@title Embodied Browsing (VR as First-Class Navigation)
@audience VR interaction designers, digital library architects
@tone analytic
@style design-pattern
@sigils [🥽/体]
@references [vsatlatarium/dome-projection vsatlas/community-engagement]

! conclusion:
  Treat VR headset navigation as a first-class mode where the viewer's body
  (head orientation, hand pointing, controller buttons) replaces mouse and
  scroll as the primary interface to the constellation.

  + context: You are designing for immersive hardware (Quest 2/3, future AR) where the viewer is physically inside the dome. This does not apply to desktop-only deployments.
  + IF:
    The planetarium metaphor maps naturally to VR — the viewer is literally
    inside a sphere of stories.

  + HOWEVER:
    Porting mouse interactions to VR produces clumsy, imprecise pointing
    at small targets with no tactile feedback.

  + THEN:
    Add generous invisible hit volumes around nodes and labels, use
    controller buttons for structural navigation (B = back to
    planetarium), and keep the viewer inside the scene rather than
    navigating away (overlay architecture for story reading).

  + BECAUSE:
    Embodied interfaces reward spatial memory — viewers remember where a
    story is in the dome and reach for it, building familiarity through
    physical gesture rather than text search.

  + STATUS:
    status[ready]
    evidence[VSATLATARIUM Quest 2 support — hit spheres, B-button back-nav, laser-controls]

  + NEXT-STEPS:
    next[Prototype the overlay architecture so story-reading stays inside the planetarium scene.]
    next[Test with AR passthrough to see if the dome works as a mixed-reality installation.]
    next[Measure whether VR visitors explore more stories than desktop visitors (spatial memory effect).]
